<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the TWO `sys_choice` rows
    that enumerate the legal values of the `party_type` Choice field on the
    `x_[scope]_case_party` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field        Type     Constraints
        party_type   Choice   Person, Organization

    The values authored here are the AAP-mandated CLOSED enumeration for
    THIS POC build - exactly two records, no more and no fewer. AAP
    Section 0.5.7 verbatim limits this Choice list to two values, and the
    MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2 prohibits adding any third
    value (e.g., `Group`, `Department`, `Anonymous`) without explicit AAP
    authorization, since each new party type would require:
        (a) a new `sys_choice` row in this file
        (b) a new conditional reference field in
            ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml (e.g., a `group` reference
            for `party_type=Group`)
        (c) a new dictionary entry for that conditional reference field
        (d) updates to the UI Policy in
            ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml so
            the new conditional field's visibility is wired to the new
            choice value
        (e) updates to seed data in ../seed-data/parties/
    Adding a third value here without parts (b)-(e) would leave the new
    party type without a destination reference field, breaking the AAP
    Section 0.4.3 polymorphism pattern.

    THIS CHOICE LIST IS THE DRIVER OF THE AAP'S POLYMORPHIC ASSOCIATION
    DESIGN PATTERN (AAP Section 0.4.3): "Polymorphic association via
    single-table choice + UI Policy". Per AAP Section 0.4.3, the UI
    Policy's visibility logic (../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml)
    uses the EXACT case-sensitive label values declared below:
        When `party_type = Person`:
            - the `person` reference field (-> sys_user) is visible and mandatory
            - the `organization` reference field is hidden and not mandatory
        When `party_type = Organization`:
            - the `organization` reference field (-> core_company) is visible and mandatory
            - the `person` reference field is hidden and not mandatory
    If a label here changes, the UI Policy condition expressions
    (`current.party_type == 'Person'`, `current.party_type == 'Organization'`)
    MUST change in lockstep. The labels are case-sensitive: `Person`
    (Title Case), NOT `person` (lowercase), NOT `PERSON` (uppercase),
    NOT `People` (plural), NOT `Persons` (plural). Likewise, `Organization`
    (Title Case, American spelling with `z`), NOT `organization` (lowercase),
    NOT `Organisation` (British spelling), NOT `Org` (abbreviation), NOT
    `Organizations` (plural).

    Per AAP Sections 0.5.2 and 0.4.1, the labels declared here are
    additionally read by:

      The parent dictionary entry that declares this field as Choice:
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml
            (mandatory=true, choice=3 means "Choice list - dropdown only",
            max_length=40 which accommodates both `Person` (6 chars) and
            `Organization` (12 chars) with margin for any future extension
            authorized by a subsequent AAP)

      The synthetic demo parties satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1:
        ../seed-data/parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml
            (each demo party row picks one of these two values; per AAP
            Section 0.3.1 "at least one Person and one Organization party
            per demo case to exercise the polymorphic UI policy" the
            seed set MUST include both values to validate the UI Policy
            at PDI re-import time)

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.2.1.3:
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonAssociation.java
        line 70-72:
            @Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)
            @DiscriminatorColumn(name = "cm_class_name", discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)
            @DiscriminatorValue("com.armedia.acm.plugins.person.model.PersonAssociation")
        ArkCase's discriminator strategy stores the Java FULLY-QUALIFIED
        CLASS NAME (e.g., `com.armedia.acm.plugins.person.model.PersonAssociation`)
        in the `cm_class_name` column. This is opaque to non-Java
        consumers, fragile under refactors (rename a class - all rows
        break), and mixed-pattern (the second association table
        PersonOrganizationAssociation lives in a separate table with a
        DIFFERENT discriminator value). The ServiceNow target FIXES
        this by collapsing both ArkCase tables into ONE table
        (x_[scope]_case_party) with a HUMAN-READABLE choice
        discriminator (`Person` | `Organization`), enforced at
        platform-validation time through the parent dictionary entry's
        `<choice>3</choice>` setting in
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonOrganizationAssociation.java
        line 64-68:
            @Entity
            @Table(name = "acm_person_org_assoc")
            @Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)
            @DiscriminatorColumn(name = "cm_class_name", ...)
            @DiscriminatorValue("com.armedia.acm.plugins.person.model.PersonOrganizationAssociation")
        ArkCase's second association table is a SEPARATE Hibernate entity
        in a DIFFERENT physical table (`acm_person_org_assoc`), with both
        Person and Organization references via @ManyToOne. The target
        collapses both ArkCase tables (acm_person_assoc and
        acm_person_org_assoc) into ONE ServiceNow polymorphic table
        with conditional reference fields - eliminating the dual-table
        complexity in favor of declarative single-table inheritance.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - EXACTLY two records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The two records below are the COMPLETE enumeration
        for this POC build.
      - Title Case labels: `Person`, `Organization`. NOT uppercase
        (ArkCase legacy convention used FQCNs which were mixed-case),
        NOT lowercase, NOT camelCase, NOT plural.
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-readable
        label - no integer codes, no enum ordinals, no separate
        machine-key. This matches the pattern used by sibling Choice
        lists in this app (sys_choice_case_status, sys_choice_case_type,
        sys_choice_case_priority, sys_choice_case_pending_reason,
        sys_choice_case_task_type, sys_choice_case_task_status) and is
        essential for the UI Policy condition expression equality check
        (`current.party_type == 'Person'`,
        `current.party_type == 'Organization'`) to work without
        translation, and for the seed-data XML to populate the field
        directly without reverse-mapping.
      - Sequence ordering matches the AAP Section 0.5.7 listing order
        (`Person, Organization`) in increments of 100:
            Person (100) -> Organization (200)
        Per the agent prompt's Key Insights item 6, this puts Person
        first in the dropdown which matches typical UX expectations
        (most case-management party associations are people, with
        organizations being a less common variant). The increment-of-100
        spacing leaves room for inserting new values (e.g.,
        `Group` at 150) without renumbering existing rows, though the
        AAP MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits adding any in this POC.
      - Both records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value is
        active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no deprecated
        legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: per the agent prompt's Key Insights item
        7, this is a flat choice list. The dependency runs in the
        OPPOSITE direction - this `party_type` field DRIVES the
        visibility/required state of the `person` and `organization`
        reference fields, but that is enforced by the UI Policy in
        ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml, NOT
        by the Choice's `dependent_value` mechanism (which would make
        THIS field DEPEND on another field, the inverse of what is
        wanted here).
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting (Person and
        Organization are universally understood party-type terms). The
        agent prompt explicitly suppresses helper text per the POC scope.
      - No default value at this Choice level: per the parent dictionary
        entry ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml which
        has an empty <default_value/>, the user MUST explicitly pick one
        of these two values. Per the agent prompt's Key Insights item 5,
        this makes the polymorphic intent unambiguous - there is no
        "default" party type. Defaulting to either would auto-populate
        the `person` or `organization` reference field's
        visibility/required state in the UI Policy without an explicit
        user choice, which would be confusing in a polymorphic
        association.
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_[scope]`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope
        writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role,
        core_company, task, incident, etc. are never modified by these
        records (the `core_company` reference in the sibling
        `organization` field is a READ-ONLY foreign-key reference, not
        a write to that table).
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_[scope]_case_party.party_type.<Value>` so that
        re-generation of this XML yields byte-identical output (no
        random UUIDs). Per the agent prompt's Key Insights item 10,
        this is the record's own primary key, NOT a forbidden reference
        to another record. The MD5 inputs are documented adjacent to
        each record below for full traceability.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention; the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App
        Engine Studio creation time, which the import process resolves
        into the final scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every record
        per the POC scope. The platform supports localization via
        additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but no
        non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical classification terms only;
        no real names, email addresses, or organizational identifiers
        are derived from or stored in these records.
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict
        XML conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview
        (AAP Section 0.7.3 validation gate 7).

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml (parent table; party_type
          field's host)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_party_type.xml (parent
          dictionary entry; declares the column shape, choice=3,
          mandatory=true, max_length=40. Without this entry the
          sys_choice records below have no column to attach to.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE:
        - ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
            (the UI Policy uses these EXACT case-sensitive label values
            for visibility logic - condition expressions check
            `current.party_type == 'Person'` and
            `current.party_type == 'Organization'`)
        - ../seed-data/parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml
            (each demo party sets this field; values must match the
            labels here byte-for-byte for the GlideRecord seed lookups
            by `case` number to populate the party_type field correctly)

      Loading order is enforced by the alphabetical Update Set preview
      ordering plus the record-by-record dependency-resolution pass.

    The MD5 input for each record's <sys_id> is the canonical identifier
    <table>.<element>.<value>, matching the convention used by the
    sibling Choice files (sys_choice_case_status, sys_choice_case_type,
    sys_choice_case_task_status):
        MD5("x_[scope]_case_party.party_type.Person")       = 8980a8a92620d4409c084f61a81d5dcb
        MD5("x_[scope]_case_party.party_type.Organization") = 1c3db1ba6f9ad0bac44139983f64f7d5
    These hashes are recomputable from the AAP-mandated canonical input,
    guaranteeing deterministic XML re-generation across all build runs.
-->
